For the CARES ACT Choctaw Nation of Oklahoma-Students that qualify please make sure to fill out for the COVID-19 Technology Program as soon as possible. Thank you!

Program summary
COVID-19 TECHNOLOGY PROGRAM ($400)
Program Summary
The COVID-19 Technology Program is offered to equip all school age Choctaw children with technology tools, such as laptops and internet access, that will better enable distance learning necessitated by COVID-19. Eligible applicants would receive a one-time $400 allowance per eligible Choctaw dependent. To receive this assistance, Choctaw Nation tribal members will be required to attest that their child's or children's learning opportunities have been negatively impacted by the COVID-19 Public Health Emergency.

Eligible Age: 5 to 18; must currently be an enrolled, non-post-secondary student to qualify.
Application Dates: July 6, 2020 to September 30, 2020
Benefit: $400 per eligible Choctaw Nation tribal member
Service Area: National

Deadline for OKPromise application is this coming Tuesday, June30!

Please share the following link with your parents and students: https://myokpromise.org/



If your student was in the 10th grade during the 2019-20 school year and you anticipate that your 2020 income may be under the $55,000 application limit for the Oklahoma‚Äôs Promise scholarship due to recent reductions in your income, you may submit an application based on your 2020 estimated income.

The application must be submitted prior to the June 30, 2020 deadline at https://secure.okcollegestart.org/applications/Oklahoma_Promise/apply.html. You will be required to provide a copy of your 2020 federal tax return when completed to verify that your 2020 income was under $55,000. The application will be held as pending until the tax documentation is received. Please send any questions to okpromise@osrhe.edu.

post_text: Our Battiest Community. As the Corona virus continues to accelerate in the number of cases, the state health department and the CDC warn us to expect a spike in cases over the next few weeks. As a result we have made the decision to provide students with one and only one packet of educational material for enrichment this next Tuesday that will be for the entire final month of school. This will be for personal enrichment and therefore optional. These packets will not be returned. In addition we will be sending home anything your elementary child may have had left in their desk or locker. Please return any textbooks or library books to the driver or to the school on Tuesday. We hope that by reducing contact in the weeks to come we can continue to keep our community isolated as much as possible and therefore safe. Students enjoy your extended summer.

Hello all parents. As many of you know by now, The State of Oklahoma has ordered all school BUILDINGS closed through the end of the year.

However we have been told to begin distance learning starting the week of April 6th. Therefore, April 7th we will begin delivering packets of work weekly on Tuesdays and picking up the completed packet the following Tuesday.

The packets should be primarily review in nature and a lite version of their normal school work. A link is included that will help us know where and when you would like to receive your child's work.

post_text: Good evening. This is an important message for Battiest Schools families. This afternoon, the state Board of Education voted to close all Oklahoma schools, effective immediately, until at least April 6 in an effort to minimize the spread of COVID-19. This means, following spring break, Battiest students will not return to school for at least two weeks, and possibly longer, if health officials deem it necessary. Employees will receive information about their responsibilities during the school closure over the next few days. Again, there will be no school for Battiest students until at least April 6. Thank you for your flexibility and understanding. Please be safe and have a wonderful evening.

post_text:
Congratulations to the Battiest high school slowpitch softball team on winning the Clayton Invitational tournament last night! It was a long day with six games. 103 runs and 18 homeruns on the day. Played first game at 10:00 a.m. and finished last game at 11:03 p.m. last night. Despite being exhausted we never gave up and fought hard until the end.
Super proud of these girls and the effort they showed last night.
Game 1 versus Stringtown won 14-5.
Game 2 versus Smithville won 15-7.
Game 3 versus Clayton lost 16-21.
Game 4 versus Smithville won 16-13.
Game 5 versus Clayton won 24-16. (CHAMPIONSHIP)
Game 6 versus Clayton won 18-16. (CHAMPIONSHIP)
Good job girls!

Smiles were many among the residents at both places. We got to see MC Jacob's, former member of the Bethel community. He got to relive many fond memories while hearing many familiar names. Personally, I was blessed to talk with Mrs. Pearl Sharrock Carol Sharrock Long David Sharrock and my longtime friend‚Ä¶ More

The Elementary kids were challenged to read 9,185,000 words during the 1st Semester Principal Reading Challenge!
They far surpassed that number and ended with 10,584,421 words! So the top readers in each class got to put a pie in Mrs.Davis face! Good job kids!

Battiest FFA
December 15, 2019 at 9:44 PM ¬∑

FFA members from around the state gathered this weekend in OKC for the annual Made for Excellence/Advanced Leadership Development conferences! Battiest members include Reanna DeLozier, Jayc DeLozier, Kace McDonald, Blaine Plemmons, Ryley Smith, Shaylyn DeLozier, Carli LeForce, Zoe McDonald, Luke DeLozier, Weston Davis, and Sydney Tyler. Students had a blast, learned a lot, and met new friends!

Battiest FFA
December 13, 2019 at 1:15 PM ¬∑

2019 Livestock Handling Team won 1st in the skills portion and 5th overall team in the State Livestock Handling Contest in Tulsa. Team members Reanna DeLozier, Bryson Berry, and Luke DeLozier all received scholarships. The chapter also received $500.
